# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: specific-ion-interaction-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In chemistry, an **acid dissociation constant** (also known as **acidity constant**, or **acid-ionization constant**; denoted ⁠ $K_{a}$ ⁠) is a quantitative measure of the strength of an acid in solution.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] known as dissociation in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The chemical species HA is an acid that dissociates into A−, called the conjugate base of the acid, and a hydrogen ion, H+.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The system is said to be in equilibrium when the concentrations of its components do not change over time, because both forward and backward reactions are occurring at the same rate.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where quantities in square brackets represent the molar concentrations of the species at equilibrium.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, a hypothetical weak acid having *K*a = 10−5, the value of log *K*a is the exponent (−5), giving p*K*a = 5.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A lower *K*a corresponds to a weaker acid (an acid that is less dissociated at equilibrium).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The form p*K*a is often used because it provides a convenient logarithmic scale, and a lower p*K*a corresponds to a stronger acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The acid dissociation constant for an acid is a direct consequence of the underlying thermodynamics of the dissociation reaction; the p*K*a value is directly proportional to the standard Gibbs free energy change for the reaction.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The value of the p*K*a changes with temperature and can be understood qualitatively based on Le Chatelier's principle: when the reaction is endothermic, *K*a increases and p*K*a decreases with increasing temperature; the opposite is true for exothermic reactions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The value of p*K*a also depends on molecular structure of the acid in many ways.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, Linus Pauling proposed two rules: one for successive p*K*a of polyprotic acids (see Polyprotic acids below), and one to estimate the p*K*a of oxyacids based on the number of =O and −OH groups (see Factors that affect p*K*a values below).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other structural factors that influence the magnitude of the acid dissociation constant include inductive effects, mesomeric effects, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Hammett type equations have frequently been applied to the estimation of p*K*a.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The quantitative behaviour of acids and bases in solution can be understood only if their p*K*a values are known.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In particular, the pH of a solution can be predicted when the analytical concentration and p*K*a values of all acids and bases are known; conversely, it is possible to calculate the equilibrium concentration of the acids and bases in solution when the pH is known.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These calculations find application in many different areas of chemistry, biology, medicine, and geology.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, many compounds used for medication are weak acids or bases, and a knowledge of the p*K*a values, together with the octanol-water partition coefficient, can be used for estimating the extent to which the compound enters the blood stream.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acid dissociation constants are also essential in aquatic chemistry and chemical oceanography, where the acidity of water plays a fundamental role.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In living organisms, acid–base homeostasis and enzyme kinetics are dependent on the p*K*a values of the many acids and bases present in the cell and in the body.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In chemistry, a knowledge of p*K*a values is necessary for the preparation of buffer solutions and is also a prerequisite for a quantitative understanding of the interaction between acids or bases and metal ions to form complexes.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Experimentally, p*K*a values can be determined by potentiometric (pH) titration, but for values of p*K*a less than about 2 or more than about 11, spectrophotometric or NMR measurements may be required due to practical difficulties with pH measurements.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The equilibrium constant for this dissociation reaction is known as a dissociation constant.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The acid loses a proton, leaving a conjugate base; the proton is transferred to the base, creating a conjugate acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For aqueous solutions of an acid HA, the base is water; the conjugate base is A− and the conjugate acid is the hydronium ion.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The Brønsted–Lowry definition applies to other solvents, such as dimethyl sulfoxide: the solvent S acts as a base, accepting a proton and forming the conjugate acid SH+.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In solution chemistry, it is common to use H+ as an abbreviation for the solvated hydrogen ion, regardless of the solvent.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aqueous solution H+ denotes a solvated hydronium ion rather than a proton.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The designation of an acid or base as "conjugate" depends on the context.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The hydroxide ion OH−, a well known base, is here acting as the conjugate base of the acid water.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acids and bases are thus regarded simply as donors and acceptors of protons respectively.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A broader definition of acid dissociation includes hydrolysis, in which protons are produced by the splitting of water molecules.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] According to Lewis's original definition, an acid is a substance that accepts an electron pair to form a coordinate covalent bond.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid dissociation constant is a particular example of an equilibrium constant.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where $\{X\}$ represents the activity, at equilibrium, of the chemical species X. $K^{\ominus }$ is dimensionless since activity is dimensionless.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Activities of the products of dissociation are placed in the numerator, activities of the reactants are placed in the denominator.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] See activity coefficient for a derivation of this expression.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where $[{\text{HA}}]$ represents the concentration of HA and ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠ is a quotient of activity coefficients.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To avoid the complications involved in using activities, dissociation constants are determined, where possible, in a medium of high ionic strength, that is, under conditions in which ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠ can be assumed to be always constant.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the medium might be a solution of 0.1 molar (M) sodium nitrate or 3 M potassium perchlorate.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note, however, that all published dissociation constant values refer to the specific ionic medium used in their determination and that different values are obtained with different conditions, as shown for acetic acid in the illustration above.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When published constants refer to an ionic strength other than the one required for a particular application, they may be adjusted by means of specific ion theory (SIT) and other theories.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note that in the context of metal-ligand complex formation, the equilibrium constants for the formation of metal complexes are usually defined as *association* constants.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In that case, the equilibrium constants for ligand protonation are also defined as association constants.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When discussing the properties of acids it is usual to specify equilibrium constants as acid dissociation constants, denoted by *K*a, with numerical values given the symbol p*K*a.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] On the other hand, association constants are used for bases.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] However, general purpose computer programs that are used to derive equilibrium constant values from experimental data use association constants for both acids and bases.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Because stability constants for a metal-ligand complex are always specified as association constants, ligand protonation must also be specified as an association reaction.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The association constant for the formation of a supramolecular complex may be denoted as Ka; in such cases "a" stands for "association", not "acid".
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For polyprotic acids, the numbering of stepwise association constants is the reverse of the numbering of the dissociation constants.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] ⁠ R ⁠ is the gas constant and ⁠ T ⁠ is the absolute temperature.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Thus, for exothermic reactions, the standard enthalpy change, ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠, is negative and *K* decreases with temperature.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For endothermic reactions, ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠ is positive and *K* increases with temperature.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where ⁠ $\Delta C_{p}$ ⁠ is the heat capacity change at constant pressure.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In practice ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠ may be taken to be constant over a small temperature range.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Express each concentration value as the ratio c/c0, where c0 is the concentration in a [hypothetical] standard state, with a numerical value of 1, by definition.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Express the concentrations on the mole fraction scale.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Since mole fraction has no dimension, the quotient of concentrations will, by definition, be a pure number.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The first and second options above give identical numerical values for an equilibrium constant.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is common practice in biochemistry to quote a value with a dimension as, for example, "*K*a = 30 mM" in order to indicate the scale, millimolar (mM) or micromolar (μM) of the concentration values used for its calculation.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid is classified as "strong" when the concentration of its undissociated species is too low to be measured.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Any aqueous acid with a p*K*a value of less than 0 is almost completely deprotonated and is considered a *strong acid*.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] All such acids transfer their protons to water and form the solvent cation species (H3O+ in aqueous solution) so that they all have essentially the same acidity, a phenomenon known as solvent leveling.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] They are said to be *fully dissociated* in aqueous solution because the amount of undissociated acid, in equilibrium with the dissociation products, is below the detection limit.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Likewise, any aqueous base with an association constant p*K*b less than about 0, corresponding to p*K*a greater than about 14, is leveled to OH− and is considered a *strong base*.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Nitric acid, with a p*K* value of around −1.7, behaves as a strong acid in aqueous solutions with a pH greater than 1.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At lower pH values it behaves as a weak acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*K*a values for strong acids have been estimated by theoretical means.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the p*K*a value of aqueous HCl has been estimated as −9.3.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is the Henderson–Hasselbalch equation, from which the following conclusions can be drawn.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In water, measurable p*K*a values range from about −2 for a strong acid to about 12 for a very weak acid (or strong base).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A buffer solution of a desired pH can be prepared as a mixture of a weak acid and its conjugate base.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In practice, the mixture can be created by dissolving the acid in water, and adding the requisite amount of strong acid or base.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the p*K*a and analytical concentration of the acid are known, the extent of dissociation and pH of a solution of a monoprotic acid can be easily calculated using an ICE table.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A polyprotic acid is a compound which may lose more than 1 proton.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Stepwise dissociation constants are each defined for the loss of a single proton.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The constant for dissociation of the first proton may be denoted as *K*a1 and the constants for dissociation of successive protons as *K*a2, etc.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Phosphoric acid, H3PO4, is an example of a polyprotic acid as it can lose three protons.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The species distribution diagram shows that the concentrations of the two ions are maximum at pH 5.5 and 10.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the difference between successive p*K* values is less than about four there is overlap between the pH range of existence of the species in equilibrium.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The smaller the difference, the more the overlap.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The case of citric acid is shown at the right; solutions of citric acid are buffered over the whole range of pH 2.5 to 7.5.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] According to Pauling's first rule, successive p*K* values of a given acid increase (p*K*a2 > p*K*a1).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For oxyacids with more than one ionizable hydrogen on the same atom, the p*K*a values often increase by about 5 units for each proton removed, as in the example of phosphoric acid above.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It can be seen in the table above that the second proton is removed from a negatively charged species.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Since the proton carries a positive charge extra work is needed to remove it, which is why p*K*a2 is greater than p*K*a1. p*K*a3 is greater than p*K*a2 because there is further charge separation.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When an exception to Pauling's rule is found, it indicates that a major change in structure is also occurring.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the case of VO+2(aq), the vanadium is octahedral, 6-coordinate, whereas vanadic acid is tetrahedral, 4-coordinate.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This means that four "particles" are released with the first dissociation, but only two "particles" are released with the other dissociations, resulting in a much greater entropy contribution to the standard Gibbs free energy change for the first reaction than for the others.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For substances in solution, the isoelectric point (p*I*) is defined as the pH at which the sum, weighted by charge value, of concentrations of positively charged species is equal to the weighted sum of concentrations of negatively charged species.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the case that there is one species of each type, the isoelectric point can be obtained directly from the p*K* values.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Take the example of glycine, defined as AH.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] There are two dissociation equilibria to consider.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*I* values for amino acids are listed at proteinogenic amino acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When more than two charged species are in equilibrium with each other a full speciation calculation may be needed.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When *K*a, *K*b and *K*w are determined under the same conditions of temperature and ionic strength, it follows, taking cologarithms, that p*K*b = p*K*w − p*K*a.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] with sufficient accuracy for most practical purposes.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In effect there is no need to define p*K*b separately from p*K*a, but it is done here as often only p*K*b values can be found in the older literature.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is the reciprocal of an association constant for formation of the complex.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Because the relationship p*K*b = p*K*w − p*K*a holds only in aqueous solutions (though analogous relationships apply for other amphoteric solvents), subdisciplines of chemistry like organic chemistry that usually deal with nonaqueous solutions generally do not use p*K*b as a measure of basicity.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Instead, the p*K*a of the conjugate acid, denoted by p*K*aH, is quoted when basicity needs to be quantified.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A higher value for p*K*aH corresponds to a stronger base.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the values p*K*aH (C5H5N) = 5.25 and p*K*aH ((CH3CH2)3N) = 10.75 indicate that (CH3CH2)3N (triethylamine) is a stronger base than C5H5N (pyridine).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An amphoteric substance is one that can act as an acid or as a base, depending on pH.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Carbonic acid equilibria are important for acid–base homeostasis in the human body.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An amino acid is also amphoteric with the added complication that the neutral molecule is subject to an internal acid–base equilibrium in which the basic amino group attracts and binds the proton from the acidic carboxyl group, forming a zwitterion.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At pH less than about 5 both the carboxylate group and the amino group are protonated.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At high pH a second dissociation may take place.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Thus the amino acid molecule is amphoteric because it may either be protonated or deprotonated.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The water molecule may either gain or lose a proton.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where in aqueous solution H+ denotes a solvated proton.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Often this is written as the hydronium ion H3O+, but this formula is not exact because in fact there is solvation by more than one water molecule and species such as H5O+2, H7O+3, and H9O+4 are also present.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The self-ionization constant of water, *K*w, is thus just a special case of an acid dissociation constant.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At that temperature both hydrogen and hydroxide ions have a concentration of 10−7 M.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a high donor number, making it a strong Lewis base.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a high dielectric constant (relative permittivity), making it a good solvent for ionic species.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*K*a values of organic compounds are often obtained using the aprotic solvents dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO) and acetonitrile (ACN).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] DMSO is widely used as an alternative to water because it has a lower dielectric constant than water, and is less polar and so dissolves non-polar, hydrophobic substances more easily.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a measurable p*K*a range of about 1 to 30.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acetonitrile is less basic than DMSO, and, so, in general, acids are weaker and bases are stronger in this solvent.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Some p*K*a values at 25 °C for acetonitrile (ACN) and dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO). are shown in the following tables.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Values for water are included for comparison.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ionization of acids is less in an acidic solvent than in water.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, hydrogen chloride is a weak acid when dissolved in acetic acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is because acetic acid is a much weaker base than water.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The unlikely geminal diol species CH3C(OH)+2 is stable in these environments.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For aqueous solutions the pH scale is the most convenient acidity function.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other acidity functions have been proposed for non-aqueous media, the most notable being the Hammett acidity function, *H*0, for superacid media and its modified version *H*− for superbasic media.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aprotic solvents, oligomers, such as the well-known acetic acid dimer, may be formed by hydrogen bonding.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid may also form hydrogen bonds to its conjugate base.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This process, known as homoconjugation, has the effect of enhancing the acidity of acids, lowering their effective p*K*a values, by stabilizing the conjugate base.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Homoconjugation enhances the proton-donating power of toluenesulfonic acid in acetonitrile solution by a factor of nearly 800.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aqueous solutions, homoconjugation does not occur, because water forms stronger hydrogen bonds to the conjugate base than does the acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When a compound has limited solubility in water it is common practice (in the pharmaceutical industry, for example) to determine p*K*a values in a solvent mixture such as water/dioxane or water/methanol, in which the compound is more soluble.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the example shown at the right, the p*K*a value rises steeply with increasing percentage of dioxane as the dielectric constant of the mixture is decreasing.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A p*K*a value obtained in a mixed solvent cannot be used directly for aqueous solutions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The reason for this is that when the solvent is in its standard state its activity is *defined* as one.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the standard state of water:dioxane mixture with 9:1 mixing ratio is precisely that solvent mixture, with no added solutes.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To obtain the p*K*a value for use with aqueous solutions it has to be extrapolated to zero co-solvent concentration from values obtained from various co-solvent mixtures.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These facts are obscured by the omission of the solvent from the expression that is normally used to define p*K*a, but p*K*a values obtained in a *given* mixed solvent can be compared to each other, giving relative acid strengths.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The same is true of p*K*a values obtained in a particular non-aqueous solvent such a DMSO.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A universal, solvent-independent, scale for acid dissociation constants has not been developed, since there is no known way to compare the standard states of two different solvents.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Pauling's second rule is that the value of the first p*K*a for acids of the formula XO*m*(OH)*n* depends primarily on the number of oxo groups *m*, and is approximately independent of the number of hydroxy groups *n*, and also of the central atom X.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Alternatively, various numerical formulas have been proposed including p*K*a = 8 − 5*m* (known as Bell's rule), p*K*a = 7 − 5*m*, or p*K*a = 9 − 7*m*.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The dependence on *m* correlates with the oxidation state of the central atom, X: the higher the oxidation state the stronger the oxyacid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, p*K*a for HClO is 7.2, for HClO2 is 2.0, for HClO3 is −1 and HClO4 is a strong acid (p*K*a ≪ 0).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The increased acidity on adding an oxo group is due to stabilization of the conjugate base by delocalization of its negative charge over an additional oxygen atom.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This rule can help assign molecular structure: for example, phosphorous acid, having molecular formula H3PO3, has a p*K*a near 2, which suggested that the structure is HPO(OH)2, as later confirmed by NMR spectroscopy, and not P(OH)3, which would be expected to have a p*K*a near 8.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Inductive effects and mesomeric effects affect the p*K*a values.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A simple example is provided by the effect of replacing the hydrogen atoms in acetic acid by the more electronegative chlorine atom.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The electron-withdrawing effect of the substituent makes ionisation easier, so successive p*K*a values decrease in the series 4.7, 2.8, 1.4, and 0.7 when 0, 1, 2, or 3 chlorine atoms are present.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The Hammett equation, provides a general expression for the effect of substituents.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Alcohols do not normally behave as acids in water, but the presence of a double bond adjacent to the OH group can substantially decrease the p*K*a by the mechanism of keto–enol tautomerism.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ascorbic acid is an example of this effect.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The diketone 2,4-pentanedione (acetylacetone) is also a weak acid because of the keto–enol equilibrium.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aromatic compounds, such as phenol, which have an OH substituent, conjugation with the aromatic ring as a whole greatly increases the stability of the deprotonated form.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Structural effects can also be important.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The difference between fumaric acid and maleic acid is a classic example.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Fumaric acid is (E)-1,4-but-2-enedioic acid, a *trans* isomer, whereas maleic acid is the corresponding *cis* isomer, i.e.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] (Z)-1,4-but-2-enedioic acid (see cis-trans isomerism).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Fumaric acid has p*K*a values of approximately 3.0 and 4.5.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] By contrast, maleic acid has p*K*a values of approximately 1.5 and 6.5.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The reason for this large difference is that when one proton is removed from the *cis* isomer (maleic acid) a strong intramolecular hydrogen bond is formed with the nearby remaining carboxyl group.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This favors the formation of the maleate H+, and it opposes the removal of the second proton from that species.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the *trans* isomer, the two carboxyl groups are always far apart, so hydrogen bonding is not observed.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Proton sponge, 1,8-bis(dimethylamino)naphthalene, has a p*K*a value of 12.1.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is one of the strongest amine bases known.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The high basicity is attributed to the relief of strain upon protonation and strong internal hydrogen bonding.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Effects of the solvent and solvation should be mentioned also in this section.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It turns out, these influences are more subtle than that of a dielectric medium mentioned above.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the expected (by electronic effects of methyl substituents) and observed in gas phase order of basicity of methylamines, Me3N > Me2NH > MeNH2 > NH3, is changed by water to Me2NH > MeNH2 > Me3N > NH3.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Neutral methylamine molecules are hydrogen-bonded to water molecules mainly through one acceptor, N–HOH, interaction and only occasionally just one more donor bond, NH–OH2.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Hence, methylamines are stabilized to about the same extent by hydration, regardless of the number of methyl groups.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In stark contrast, corresponding methylammonium cations always utilize **all** the available protons for donor NH–OH2 bonding.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Relative stabilization of methylammonium ions thus decreases with the number of methyl groups explaining the order of water basicity of methylamines.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The standard enthalpy change can be determined by calorimetry or by using the van 't Hoff equation, though the calorimetric method is preferable.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When both the standard enthalpy change and acid dissociation constant have been determined, the standard entropy change is easily calculated from the equation above.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the following table, the entropy terms are calculated from the experimental values of p*K*a and Δ*H*⊖.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The data were critically selected and refer to 25 °C and zero ionic strength, in water.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The first point to note is that, when p*K*a is positive, the standard free energy change for the dissociation reaction is also positive.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Second, some reactions are exothermic and some are endothermic, but, when Δ*H*⊖ is negative *T*ΔS⊖ is the dominant factor, which determines that Δ*G*⊖ is positive.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Last, the entropy contribution is always unfavourable (Δ*S*⊖ < 0) in these reactions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ions in aqueous solution tend to orient the surrounding water molecules, which orders the solution and decreases the entropy.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The contribution of an ion to the entropy is the partial molar entropy which is often negative, especially for small or highly charged ions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The ionization of a neutral acid involves formation of two ions so that the entropy decreases (Δ*S*⊖ < 0).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] On the second ionization of the same acid, there are now three ions and the anion has a charge, so the entropy again decreases.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note that the *standard* free energy change for the reaction is for the changes *from* the reactants in their standard states *to* the products in their standard states.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The free energy change *at* equilibrium is zero since the chemical potentials of reactants and products are equal at equilibrium.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The experimental determination of p*K*a values is commonly performed by means of titrations, in a medium of high ionic strength and at constant temperature.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A typical procedure would be as follows.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A solution of the compound in the medium is acidified with a strong acid to the point where the compound is fully protonated.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The solution is then titrated with a strong base until all the protons have been removed.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At each point in the titration pH is measured using a glass electrode and a pH meter.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The equilibrium constants are found by fitting calculated pH values to the observed values, using the method of least squares.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The total volume of added strong base should be small compared to the initial volume of titrand solution in order to keep the ionic strength nearly constant.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This will ensure that p*K*a remains invariant during the titration.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A calculated titration curve for oxalic acid is shown at the right.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Oxalic acid has p*K*a values of 1.27 and 4.27.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Therefore, the buffer regions will be centered at about pH 1.3 and pH 4.3.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The buffer regions carry the information necessary to get the p*K*a values as the concentrations of acid and conjugate base change along a buffer region.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Between the two buffer regions there is an end-point, or equivalence point, at about pH 3.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This end-point is not sharp and is typical of a diprotic acid whose buffer regions overlap by a small amount: p*K*a2 − p*K*a1 is about three in this example.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] (If the difference in p*K* values were about two or less, the end-point would not be noticeable.) The second end-point begins at about pH 6.3 and is sharp.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This indicates that all the protons have been removed.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When this is so, the solution is not buffered and the pH rises steeply on addition of a small amount of strong base.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] However, the pH does not continue to rise indefinitely.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A new buffer region begins at about pH 11 (p*K*w − 3), which is where self-ionization of water becomes important.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is very difficult to measure pH values of less than two in aqueous solution with a glass electrode, because the Nernst equation breaks down at such low pH values.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To determine p*K* values of less than about 2 or more than about 11 spectrophotometric or NMR measurements may be used instead of, or combined with, pH measurements.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the glass electrode cannot be employed, as with non-aqueous solutions, spectrophotometric methods are frequently used.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These may involve absorbance or fluorescence measurements.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In both cases the measured quantity is assumed to be proportional to the sum of contributions from each photo-active species; with absorbance measurements the Beer–Lambert law is assumed to apply.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Isothermal titration calorimetry (ITC) may be used to determine both a p*K* value and the corresponding standard enthalpy for acid dissociation.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Software to perform the calculations is supplied by the instrument manufacturers for simple systems.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Aqueous solutions with normal water cannot be used for 1H NMR measurements but heavy water, D2O, must be used instead.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] 13C NMR data, however, can be used with normal water and 1H NMR spectra can be used with non-aqueous media.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The quantities measured with NMR are time-averaged chemical shifts, as proton exchange is fast on the NMR time-scale.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other chemical shifts, such as those of 31P can be measured.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For some polyprotic acids, dissociation (or association) occurs at more than one nonequivalent site, and the observed macroscopic equilibrium constant, or macro-constant, is a combination of micro-constants involving distinct species.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When one reactant forms two products in parallel, the macro-constant is a sum of two micro-constants, $K=K_{X}+K_{Y}.$ This is true for example for the deprotonation of the amino acid cysteine, which exists in solution as a neutral zwitterion HS−CH2−CH(NH+3)−COO−.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Similarly, a base such as spermine has more than one site where protonation can occur.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, mono-protonation can occur at a terminal −NH2 group or at internal −NH− groups.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The *K*b values for dissociation of spermine protonated at one or other of the sites are examples of micro-constants.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] They cannot be determined directly by means of pH, absorbance, fluorescence or NMR measurements; a measured *K*b value is the sum of the K values for the micro-reactions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Nevertheless, the site of protonation is very important for biological function, so mathematical methods have been developed for the determination of micro-constants.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When a reactant undergoes two reactions in series, the macro-constant for the combined reaction is the product of the micro-constant for the two steps.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A knowledge of p*K*a values is important for the quantitative treatment of systems involving acid–base equilibria in solution.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Many applications exist in biochemistry; for example, the p*K*a values of proteins and amino acid side chains are of major importance for the activity of enzymes and the stability of proteins.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Protein p*K*a values cannot always be measured directly, but may be calculated using theoretical methods.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffer solutions are used extensively to provide solutions at or near the physiological pH for the study of biochemical reactions; the design of these solutions depends on a knowledge of the p*K*a values of their components.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Important buffer solutions include MOPS, which provides a solution with pH 7.2, and tricine, which is used in gel electrophoresis.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffering is an essential part of acid base physiology including acid–base homeostasis, and is key to understanding disorders such as acid–base disorder.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The isoelectric point of a given molecule is a function of its p*K* values, so different molecules have different isoelectric points.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This permits a technique called isoelectric focusing, which is used for separation of proteins by 2-D gel polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffer solutions also play a key role in analytical chemistry.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] They are used whenever there is a need to fix the pH of a solution at a particular value.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Compared with an aqueous solution, the pH of a buffer solution is relatively insensitive to the addition of a small amount of strong acid or strong base.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The buffer capacity of a simple buffer solution is largest when pH = p*K*a.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In acid–base extraction, the efficiency of extraction of a compound into an organic phase, such as an ether, can be optimised by adjusting the pH of the aqueous phase using an appropriate buffer.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] At the optimum pH, the concentration of the electrically neutral species is maximised; such a species is more soluble in organic solvents having a low dielectric constant than it is in water.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This technique is used for the purification of weak acids and bases.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A pH indicator is a weak acid or weak base that changes colour in the transition pH range, which is approximately p*K*a ± 1.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The design of a universal indicator requires a mixture of indicators whose adjacent p*K*a values differ by about two, so that their transition pH ranges just overlap.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In pharmacology, ionization of a compound alters its physical behaviour and macro properties such as solubility and lipophilicity, log *p*).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] For example, ionization of any compound will increase the solubility in water, but decrease the lipophilicity.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This is exploited in drug development to increase the concentration of a compound in the blood by adjusting the p*K*a of an ionizable group.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Knowledge of p*K*a values is important for the understanding of coordination complexes, which are formed by the interaction of a metal ion, Mm+, acting as a Lewis acid, with a ligand, L, acting as a Lewis base.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] To determine the equilibrium constant for this reaction, in which the ligand loses a proton, the p*K*a of the protonated ligand must be known.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In practice, the ligand may be polyprotic; for example EDTA4− can accept four protons; in that case, all p*K*a values must be known.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In addition, the metal ion is subject to hydrolysis, that is, it behaves as a weak acid, so the p*K* values for the hydrolysis reactions must also be known.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Assessing the hazard associated with an acid or base may require a knowledge of p*K*a values.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] For example, hydrogen cyanide is a very toxic gas, because the cyanide ion inhibits the iron-containing enzyme cytochrome c oxidase.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Hydrogen cyanide is a weak acid in aqueous solution with a p*K*a of about 9.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In strongly alkaline solutions, above pH 11, say, it follows that sodium cyanide is "fully dissociated" so the hazard due to the hydrogen cyanide gas is much reduced.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] An acidic solution, on the other hand, is very hazardous because all the cyanide is in its acid form.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Ingestion of cyanide by mouth is potentially fatal, independently of pH, because of the reaction with cytochrome c oxidase.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In environmental science acid–base equilibria are important for lakes and rivers; for example, humic acids are important components of natural waters.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] There are multiple techniques to determine the p*K*a of a chemical, leading to some discrepancies between different sources.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Well measured values are typically within 0.1 units of each other.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Data presented here were taken at 25 °C in water.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] More values can be found in the Thermodynamics section, above.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A table of p*K*a of carbon acids, measured in DMSO, can be found on the page on carbanions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] An **acid** is a molecule or ion capable of either donating a proton (i.e. hydrogen cation, H+), known as a Brønsted–Lowry acid, or forming a covalent bond with an electron pair, known as a Lewis acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The first category of acids are the proton donors, or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In the special case of aqueous solutions, proton donors form the hydronium ion H3O+ and are known as Arrhenius acids.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Brønsted and Lowry generalized the Arrhenius theory to include non-aqueous solvents.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] A Brønsted–Lowry or Arrhenius acid usually contains a hydrogen atom bonded to a chemical structure that is still energetically favorable after loss of H+.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Aqueous Arrhenius acids have characteristic properties that provide a practical description of an acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Acids form aqueous solutions with a sour taste, can turn blue litmus red, and react with bases and certain metals (like calcium) to form salts.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The word *acid* is derived from the Latin *acidus*, meaning 'sour'.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] An aqueous solution of an acid has a pH less than 7 and is colloquially also referred to as "acid" (as in "dissolved in acid"), while the strict definition refers only to the solute.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] A lower pH means a higher **acidity**, and thus a higher concentration of hydrogen cations in the solution.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Chemicals or substances having the property of an acid are said to be **acidic**.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] As these examples show, acids (in the colloquial sense) can be solutions or pure substances, and can be derived from acids (in the strict sense) that are solids, liquids, or gases.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Strong acids and some concentrated weak acids are corrosive, but there are exceptions such as carboranes and boric acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The second category of acids are Lewis acids, which form a covalent bond with an electron pair.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] An example is boron trifluoride (BF3), whose boron atom has a vacant orbital that can form a covalent bond by sharing a lone pair of electrons on an atom in a base, for example the nitrogen atom in ammonia (NH3).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Lewis considered this as a generalization of the Brønsted definition, so that an acid is a chemical species that accepts electron pairs either directly *or* by releasing protons (H+) into the solution, which then accept electron pairs.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Hydrogen chloride, acetic acid, and most other Brønsted–Lowry acids cannot form a covalent bond with an electron pair, however, and are therefore not Lewis acids.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Conversely, many Lewis acids are not Arrhenius or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In modern terminology, an *acid* is implicitly a Brønsted acid and not a Lewis acid, since chemists almost always refer to a Lewis acid explicitly as such.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Modern definitions are concerned with the fundamental chemical reactions common to all acids.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Most acids encountered in everyday life are aqueous solutions, or can be dissolved in water, so the Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are the most relevant.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The Brønsted–Lowry definition is the most widely used definition; unless otherwise specified, acid–base reactions are assumed to involve the transfer of a proton (H+) from an acid to a base.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Hydronium ions are acids according to all three definitions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Although alcohols and amines can be Brønsted–Lowry acids, they can also function as Lewis bases due to the lone pairs of electrons on their oxygen and nitrogen atoms.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In 1884, Svante Arrhenius attributed the properties of acidity to hydrogen cations (H+), later described as protons or hydrons.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] An **Arrhenius acid** is a substance that, when added to water, increases the concentration of H+ ions in the water.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Chemists often write H+(*aq*) and refer to the hydrogen cation when describing acid–base reactions but the free hydrogen nucleus, a proton, does not exist alone in water, it exists as the **hydronium ion** (H3O+) or other forms (H5O2+, H9O4+).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid can also be described as a substance that increases the concentration of hydronium ions when added to water.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Examples include molecular substances such as hydrogen chloride and acetic acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] An Arrhenius base, on the other hand, is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide (OH−) ions when dissolved in water.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Due to this equilibrium, any increase in the concentration of hydronium is accompanied by a decrease in the concentration of hydroxide.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid could also be said to be one that decreases hydroxide concentration, while an Arrhenius base increases it.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In an acidic solution, the concentration of hydronium ions is greater than 10−7 moles per liter.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Since pH is defined as the negative logarithm of the concentration of hydronium ions, acidic solutions thus have a pH of less than 7.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] While the Arrhenius concept is useful for describing many reactions, it is also quite limited in its scope.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In 1923, chemists Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted and Thomas Martin Lowry independently recognized that acid–base reactions involve the transfer of a proton.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] A **Brønsted–Lowry acid** (or simply Brønsted acid) is a species that donates a proton to a Brønsted–Lowry base.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory has several advantages over Arrhenius theory.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Both theories easily describe the first reaction: CH3COOH acts as an Arrhenius acid because it acts as a source of H3O+ when dissolved in water, and it acts as a Brønsted acid by donating a proton to water.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In the second example CH3COOH undergoes the same transformation, in this case donating a proton to ammonia (NH3), but does not relate to the Arrhenius definition of an acid because the reaction does not produce hydronium.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Nevertheless, CH3COOH is both an Arrhenius and a Brønsted–Lowry acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Brønsted–Lowry theory can be used to describe reactions of molecular compounds in nonaqueous solution or the gas phase.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Hydrogen chloride (HCl) and ammonia combine under several different conditions to form ammonium chloride, NH4Cl.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In aqueous solution HCl behaves as hydrochloric acid and exists as hydronium and chloride ions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] As with the acetic acid reactions, both definitions work for the first example, where water is the solvent and hydronium ion is formed by the HCl solute.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The next two reactions do not involve the formation of ions but are still proton-transfer reactions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In the second reaction hydrogen chloride and ammonia (dissolved in benzene) react to form solid ammonium chloride in a benzene solvent and in the third gaseous HCl and NH3 combine to form the solid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] A third, only marginally related concept was proposed in 1923 by Gilbert N.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Lewis, which includes reactions with acid–base characteristics that do not involve a proton transfer.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] A **Lewis acid** is a species that accepts a pair of electrons from another species; in other words, it is an electron pair acceptor.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Brønsted acid–base reactions are proton transfer reactions while Lewis acid–base reactions are electron pair transfers.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Many Lewis acids are not Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In the first reaction a fluoride ion, F−, gives up an electron pair to boron trifluoride to form the product tetrafluoroborate.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Fluoride "loses" a pair of valence electrons because the electrons shared in the B—F bond are located in the region of space between the two atomic nuclei and are therefore more distant from the fluoride nucleus than they are in the lone fluoride ion.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] BF3 is a Lewis acid because it accepts the electron pair from fluoride.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] This reaction cannot be described in terms of Brønsted theory because there is no proton transfer.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The second reaction can be described using either theory.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] A proton is transferred from an unspecified Brønsted acid to ammonia, a Brønsted base; alternatively, ammonia acts as a Lewis base and transfers a lone pair of electrons to form a bond with a hydrogen ion.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The species that gains the electron pair is the Lewis acid; for example, the oxygen atom in H3O+ gains a pair of electrons when one of the H—O bonds is broken and the electrons shared in the bond become localized on oxygen.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Depending on the context, a Lewis acid may also be described as an oxidizer or an electrophile.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Organic Brønsted acids, such as acetic, citric, or oxalic acid, are not Lewis acids.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] They dissociate in water to produce a Lewis acid, H+, but at the same time, they also yield an equal amount of a Lewis base (acetate, citrate, or oxalate, respectively, for the acids mentioned).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] This article deals mostly with Brønsted acids rather than Lewis acids.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Reactions of acids are often generalized in the form HA ⇌ H+ + A−, where HA represents the acid and A− is the conjugate base.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] This reaction is referred to as **protolysis**.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The protonated form (HA) of an acid is also sometimes referred to as the **free acid**.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Acid–base conjugate pairs differ by one proton, and can be interconverted by the addition or removal of a proton (protonation and deprotonation, respectively).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The acid can be the charged species and the conjugate base can be neutral in which case the generalized reaction scheme could be written as HA+ ⇌ H+ + A.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In solution there exists an equilibrium between the acid and its conjugate base.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The equilibrium constant *K* is an expression of the equilibrium concentrations of the molecules or the ions in solution.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Brackets indicate concentration, such that [H2O] means *the concentration of H2O*.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The acid dissociation constant *K*a is generally used in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The numerical value of *K*a is equal to the product (multiplication) of the concentrations of the products divided by the concentration of the reactants, where the reactant is the acid (HA) and the products are the conjugate base and H+.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The stronger of two acids will have a higher *K*a than the weaker acid; the ratio of hydrogen cations to acid will be higher for the stronger acid as the stronger acid has a greater tendency to lose its proton.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Because the range of possible values for *K*a spans many orders of magnitude, a more manageable constant, p*K*a is more frequently used, where p*K*a = −log10 *K*a.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Stronger acids have a smaller p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Experimentally determined p*K*a at 25 °C in aqueous solution are often quoted in textbooks and reference material.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Arrhenius acids are named according to their anions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In the classical naming system, the ionic suffix is dropped and replaced with a new suffix, according to the table following.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The prefix "hydro-" is used when the acid is made up of just hydrogen and one other element.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] For example, HCl has chloride as its anion, so the hydro- prefix is used, and the -ide suffix makes the name take the form hydrochloric acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In the IUPAC naming system, "aqueous" is simply added to the name of the ionic compound.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Thus, for hydrogen chloride, as an acid solution, the IUPAC name is aqueous hydrogen chloride.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The strength of an acid refers to its ability or tendency to lose a proton.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] A strong acid is one that completely dissociates in water; in other words, one mole of a strong acid HA dissolves in water yielding one mole of H+ and one mole of the conjugate base, A−, and none of the protonated acid HA.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In contrast, a weak acid only partially dissociates and at equilibrium both the acid and the conjugate base are in solution.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Examples of strong acids are hydrochloric acid (HCl), hydroiodic acid (HI), hydrobromic acid (HBr), perchloric acid (HClO4), nitric acid (HNO3) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In water, each of these essentially ionizes 100%.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The stronger an acid is, the more easily it loses a proton, H+.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Two key factors that contribute to the ease of deprotonation are the polarity of the H—A bond and the size of atom A, which determines the strength of the H—A bond.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Acid strengths are also often discussed in terms of the stability of the conjugate base.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Stronger acids have a larger acid dissociation constant, *K*a and a lower p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Sulfonic acids, which are organic oxyacids, are a class of strong acids.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] A common example is toluenesulfonic acid (tosylic acid).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Unlike sulfuric acid itself, sulfonic acids can be solids.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In fact, polystyrene functionalized into polystyrene sulfonate is a solid strongly acidic plastic that is filterable.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Superacids are acids stronger than 100% sulfuric acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Examples of superacids are fluoroantimonic acid, magic acid and perchloric acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The strongest known acid is helium hydride ion, with a proton affinity of 177.8kJ/mol.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Superacids can permanently protonate water to give ionic, crystalline hydronium "salts".
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] They can also quantitatively stabilize carbocations.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] While *K*a measures the strength of an acid compound, the strength of an aqueous acid solution is measured by pH, which is an indication of the concentration of hydronium in the solution.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The pH of a simple solution of an acid compound in water is determined by the dilution of the compound and the compound's *K*a.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Lewis acids have been classified in the ECW model and it has been shown that there is no one order of acid strengths.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The relative acceptor strength of Lewis acids toward a series of bases, versus other Lewis acids, can be illustrated by C-B plots.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] It has been shown that to define the order of Lewis acid strength at least two properties must be considered.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] For Pearson's qualitative HSAB theory the two properties are hardness and strength while for Drago's quantitative ECW model the two properties are electrostatic and covalent.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Common examples of monoprotic acids in mineral acids include hydrochloric acid (HCl) and nitric acid (HNO3).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] On the other hand, for organic acids the term mainly indicates the presence of one carboxylic acid group and sometimes these acids are known as monocarboxylic acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Examples in organic acids include formic acid (HCOOH), acetic acid (CH3COOH) and benzoic acid (C6H5COOH).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Polyprotic acids, also known as polybasic acids, are able to donate more than one proton per acid molecule, in contrast to monoprotic acids that only donate one proton per molecule.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Specific types of polyprotic acids have more specific names, such as diprotic (or dibasic) acid (two potential protons to donate), and triprotic (or tribasic) acid (three potential protons to donate).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Some macromolecules such as proteins and nucleic acids can have a very large number of acidic protons.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] A diprotic acid (here symbolized by H2A) can undergo one or two dissociations depending on the pH.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Each dissociation has its own dissociation constant, Ka1 and Ka2.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The first dissociation constant is typically greater than the second (i.e., *K*a1 > *K*a2).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] For example, sulfuric acid (H2SO4) can donate one proton to form the bisulfate anion (HSO− 4), for which *K*a1 is very large; then it can donate a second proton to form the sulfate anion (SO2− 4), wherein the *K*a2 is intermediate strength.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The large *K*a1 for the first dissociation makes sulfuric a strong acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In a similar manner, the weak unstable carbonic acid (H2CO3) can lose one proton to form bicarbonate anion (HCO− 3) and lose a second to form carbonate anion (CO2− 3).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Both *K*a values are small, but *K*a1 > *K*a2 .
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] A triprotic acid (H3A) can undergo one, two, or three dissociations and has three dissociation constants, where *K*a1 > *K*a2 > *K*a3.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] An inorganic example of a triprotic acid is orthophosphoric acid (H3PO4), usually just called phosphoric acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] All three protons can be successively lost to yield H2PO− 4, then HPO2− 4, and finally PO3− 4, the orthophosphate ion, usually just called phosphate.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Even though the positions of the three protons on the original phosphoric acid molecule are equivalent, the successive *K*a values differ since it is energetically less favorable to lose a proton if the conjugate base is more negatively charged.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] An organic example of a triprotic acid is citric acid, which can successively lose three protons to finally form the citrate ion.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Although the subsequent loss of each hydrogen ion is less favorable, all of the conjugate bases are present in solution.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The fractional concentration, *α* (alpha), for each species can be calculated.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] For example, a generic diprotic acid will generate 3 species in solution: H2A, HA−, and A2−.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] A plot of these fractional concentrations against pH, for given *K*1 and *K*2, is known as a Bjerrum plot.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] where *K*0 = 1 and the other K-terms are the dissociation constants for the acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Neutralization is the basis of titration, where a pH indicator shows equivalence point when the equivalent number of moles of a base have been added to an acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] It is often wrongly assumed that neutralization should result in a solution with pH 7.0, which is only the case with similar acid and base strengths during a reaction.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Neutralization with a base weaker than the acid results in a weakly acidic salt.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] An example is the weakly acidic ammonium chloride, which is produced from the strong acid hydrogen chloride and the weak base ammonia.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Conversely, neutralizing a weak acid with a strong base gives a weakly basic salt (e.g., sodium fluoride from hydrogen fluoride and sodium hydroxide).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In order for a protonated acid to lose a proton, the pH of the system must rise above the p*K*a of the acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The decreased concentration of H+ in that basic solution shifts the equilibrium towards the conjugate base form (the deprotonated form of the acid).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In lower-pH (more acidic) solutions, there is a high enough H+ concentration in the solution to cause the acid to remain in its protonated form.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Solutions of weak acids and salts of their conjugate bases form buffer solutions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] To determine the concentration of an acid in an aqueous solution, an acid–base titration is commonly performed.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] A strong base solution with a known concentration, usually NaOH or KOH, is added to neutralize the acid solution according to the color change of the indicator with the amount of base added.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The titration curve of an acid titrated by a base has two axes, with the base volume on the x-axis and the solution's pH value on the y-axis.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The pH of the solution always goes up as the base is added to the solution.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] For each diprotic acid titration curve, from left to right, there are two midpoints, two equivalence points, and two buffer regions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Due to the successive dissociation processes, there are two equivalence points in the titration curve of a diprotic acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The first equivalence point occurs when all first protons from the first ionization are titrated.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In other words, the amount of OH− added equals the original amount of H2A at the first equivalence point.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The second equivalence point occurs when all protons are titrated.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Therefore, the amount of OH− added equals twice the amount of H2A at this time.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] For a weak diprotic acid titrated by a strong base, the second equivalence point must occur at pH above 7 due to the hydrolysis of the resulted salts in the solution.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] At either equivalence point, adding a drop of base will cause the steepest rise of the pH value in the system.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] A titration curve for a diprotic acid contains two midpoints where pH=pKa.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Since there are two different Ka values, the first midpoint occurs at pH=pKa1 and the second one occurs at pH=pKa2.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Each segment of the curve that contains a midpoint at its center is called the buffer region.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Because the buffer regions consist of the acid and its conjugate base, it can resist pH changes when base is added until the next equivalent points.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Acids are fundamental reagents in treating almost all processes in modern industry.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Sulfuric acid, a diprotic acid, is the most widely used acid in industry, and is also the most-produced industrial chemical in the world.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] It is mainly used in producing fertilizer, detergent, batteries and dyes, as well as used in processing many products such like removing impurities.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] According to the statistics data in 2011, the annual production of sulfuric acid was around 200 million tonnes in the world.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] For example, phosphate minerals react with sulfuric acid to produce phosphoric acid for the production of phosphate fertilizers, and zinc is produced by dissolving zinc oxide into sulfuric acid, purifying the solution and electrowinning.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In the chemical industry, acids react in neutralization reactions to produce salts.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] For example, nitric acid reacts with ammonia to produce ammonium nitrate, a fertilizer.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Additionally, carboxylic acids can be esterified with alcohols, to produce esters.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Acids are often used to remove rust and other corrosion from metals in a process known as pickling.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] They may be used as an electrolyte in a wet cell battery, such as sulfuric acid in a car battery.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Tartaric acid is an important component of some commonly used foods like unripe mangoes and tamarind.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Natural fruits and vegetables also contain acids.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Citric acid is present in oranges, lemon and other citrus fruits.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Oxalic acid is present in tomatoes, spinach, and especially in carambola and rhubarb; rhubarb leaves and unripe carambolas are toxic because of high concentrations of oxalic acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Ascorbic acid (Vitamin C) is an essential vitamin for the human body and is present in such foods as amla (Indian gooseberry), lemon, citrus fruits, and guava.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Many acids can be found in various kinds of food as additives, as they alter their taste and serve as preservatives.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Phosphoric acid, for example, is a component of cola drinks.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Acetic acid is used in day-to-day life as vinegar.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Citric acid is used as a preservative in sauces and pickles.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Carbonic acid is one of the most common acid additives that are widely added in soft drinks.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] During the manufacturing process, CO2 is usually pressurized to dissolve in these drinks to generate carbonic acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Carbonic acid is very unstable and tends to decompose into water and CO2 at room temperature and pressure.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Therefore, when bottles or cans of these kinds of soft drinks are opened, the soft drinks fizz and effervesce as CO2 bubbles come out.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Acetylsalicylic acid (Aspirin) is used as a pain killer and for bringing down fevers.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Acids play important roles in the human body.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The hydrochloric acid present in the stomach aids digestion by breaking down large and complex food molecules.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Amino acids are required for synthesis of proteins required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Fatty acids are also required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Nucleic acids are important for the manufacturing of DNA and RNA and transmitting of traits to offspring through genes.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Carbonic acid is important for maintenance of pH equilibrium in the body.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Human bodies contain a variety of organic and inorganic compounds, among those dicarboxylic acids play an essential role in many biological behaviors.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Many of those acids are amino acids, which mainly serve as materials for the synthesis of proteins.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Other weak acids serve as buffers with their conjugate bases to keep the body's pH from undergoing large scale changes that would be harmful to cells.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The rest of the dicarboxylic acids also participate in the synthesis of various biologically important compounds in human bodies.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Acids are used as catalysts in industrial and organic chemistry; for example, sulfuric acid is used in very large quantities in the alkylation process to produce gasoline.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Some acids, such as sulfuric, phosphoric, and hydrochloric acids, also effect dehydration and condensation reactions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In biochemistry, many enzymes employ acid catalysis.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Many biologically important molecules are acids.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Nucleic acids, which contain acidic phosphate groups, include DNA and RNA.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Nucleic acids contain the genetic code that determines many of an organism's characteristics, and is passed from parents to offspring.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] DNA contains the chemical blueprint for the synthesis of proteins, which are made up of amino acid subunits.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Cell membranes contain fatty acid esters such as phospholipids.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] An α-amino acid has a central carbon (the α or *alpha* carbon) that is covalently bonded to a carboxyl group (thus they are carboxylic acids), an amino group, a hydrogen atom and a variable group.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The variable group, also called the R group or side chain, determines the identity and many of the properties of a specific amino acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In glycine, the simplest amino acid, the R group is a hydrogen atom, but in all other amino acids it is contains one or more carbon atoms bonded to hydrogens, and may contain other elements such as sulfur, oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] With the exception of glycine, naturally occurring amino acids are chiral and almost invariably occur in the L-configuration.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Peptidoglycan, found in some bacterial cell walls contains some D-amino acids.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] At physiological pH, typically around 7, free amino acids exist in a charged form, where the acidic carboxyl group (-COOH) loses a proton (-COO−) and the basic amine group (-NH2) gains a proton (-NH+ 3).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The entire molecule has a net neutral charge and is a zwitterion, with the exception of amino acids with basic or acidic side chains.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Aspartic acid, for example, possesses one protonated amine and two deprotonated carboxyl groups, for a net charge of −1 at physiological pH.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Fatty acids and fatty acid derivatives are another group of carboxylic acids that play a significant role in biology.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] These contain long hydrocarbon chains and a carboxylic acid group on one end.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The cell membrane of nearly all organisms is primarily made up of a phospholipid bilayer, a micelle of hydrophobic fatty acid esters with polar, hydrophilic phosphate "head" groups.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Membranes contain additional components, some of which can participate in acid–base reactions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In humans and many other animals, hydrochloric acid is a part of the gastric acid secreted within the stomach to help hydrolyze proteins and polysaccharides, as well as converting the inactive pro-enzyme, pepsinogen into the enzyme, pepsin.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Some organisms produce acids for defense; for example, ants produce formic acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Acid–base equilibrium plays a critical role in regulating mammalian breathing.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Oxygen gas (O2) drives cellular respiration, the process by which animals release the chemical potential energy stored in food, producing carbon dioxide (CO2) as a byproduct.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Oxygen and carbon dioxide are exchanged in the lungs, and the body responds to changing energy demands by adjusting the rate of ventilation.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] For example, during periods of exertion the body rapidly breaks down stored carbohydrates and fat, releasing CO2 into the blood stream.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In aqueous solutions such as blood CO2 exists in equilibrium with carbonic acid and bicarbonate ion.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] It is the decrease in pH that signals the brain to breathe faster and deeper, expelling the excess CO2 and resupplying the cells with O2.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Cell membranes are generally impermeable to charged or large, polar molecules because of the lipophilic fatty acyl chains comprising their interior.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Many biologically important molecules, including a number of pharmaceutical agents, are organic weak acids that can cross the membrane in their protonated, uncharged form but not in their charged form (i.e., as the conjugate base).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] For this reason the activity of many drugs can be enhanced or inhibited by the use of antacids or acidic foods.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The charged form, however, is often more soluble in blood and cytosol, both aqueous environments.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] When the extracellular environment is more acidic than the neutral pH within the cell, certain acids will exist in their neutral form and will be membrane soluble, allowing them to cross the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Acids that lose a proton at the intracellular pH will exist in their soluble, charged form and are thus able to diffuse through the cytosol to their target.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Ibuprofen, aspirin and penicillin are examples of drugs that are weak acids.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] A sulfonic acid has the general formula RS(=O)2–OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] A carboxylic acid has the general formula R-C(O)OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] The carboxyl group -C(O)OH contains a carbonyl group, C=O, and a hydroxyl group, O-H.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Halogenation at alpha position increases acid strength, so that the following acids are all stronger than acetic acid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] Normal carboxylic acids are the direct union of a carbonyl group and a hydroxyl group.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/acid] In vinylogous carboxylic acids, a carbon-carbon double bond separates the carbonyl and hydroxyl groups.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] In thermodynamics, **activity** (symbol a) is a measure of the "effective concentration" of a species in a mixture, in the sense that the species' chemical potential depends on the activity of a real solution in the same way that it would depend on concentration for an ideal solution.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] The term "activity" in this sense was coined by the American chemist Gilbert N.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] By convention, activity is treated as a dimensionless quantity, although its value depends on customary choices of standard state for the species.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] The activity of pure substances in condensed phases (solids and liquids) is taken as a = 1.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Activity depends on temperature, pressure and composition of the mixture, among other things.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] For gases, the activity is the effective partial pressure, and is usually referred to as fugacity.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] The difference between activity and other measures of concentration arises because the interactions between different types of molecules in non-ideal gases or solutions are different from interactions between the same types of molecules.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] The activity of an ion is particularly influenced by its surroundings.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Equilibrium constants should be defined by activities but, in practice, are often defined by concentrations instead.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] The same is often true of equations for reaction rates.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] However, there are circumstances where the activity and the concentration are *significantly different* and, as such, it is not valid to approximate with concentrations where activities are required.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] where μi is the (molar) chemical potential of the species i under the conditions of interest, *μ*o *i* is the (molar) chemical potential of that species under some defined set of standard conditions, R is the gas constant, T is the thermodynamic temperature and e is the exponential constant.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] In general, the activity depends on any factor that alters the chemical potential.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Such factors may include: concentration, temperature, pressure, interactions between chemical species, electric fields, etc.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Depending on the circumstances, some of these factors, in particular concentration and interactions, may be more important than others.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] The activity depends on the choice of standard state such that changing the standard state will also change the activity.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] This means that activity is a relative term that describes how "active" a compound is compared to when it is under the standard state conditions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] In principle, the choice of standard state is arbitrary; however, it is often chosen out of mathematical or experimental convenience.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Note that this definition corresponds to setting as standard state the solution of $\mu _{i}=0$ , if the latter exists.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] The division by the standard molality *b*o (usually 1 mol/kg) or the standard molar concentration *c*o (usually 1 mol/L) is necessary to ensure that both the activity and the activity coefficient are dimensionless, as is conventional.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] The activity depends on the chosen standard state and composition scale; for instance, in the dilute limit it approaches the mole fraction, mass fraction, or numerical value of molarity, all of which are different.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] However, the activity coefficients are similar.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] When the activity coefficient is close to 1, the substance shows almost ideal behaviour according to Henry's law (but not necessarily in the sense of an ideal solution).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] In these cases, the activity can be substituted with the appropriate dimensionless measure of composition xi, ⁠*bi*/*b*o⁠ or ⁠*ci*/*c*o⁠.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] It is also possible to define an activity coefficient in terms of Raoult's law: the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) recommends the symbol f for this activity coefficient, although this should not be confused with fugacity.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] In most laboratory situations, the difference in behaviour between a real gas and an ideal gas is dependent only on the pressure and the temperature, not on the presence of any other gases.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] At a given temperature, the "effective" pressure of a gas i is given by its fugacity fi: this may be higher or lower than its mechanical pressure.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] where φi is the dimensionless fugacity coefficient of the species, yi is its mole fraction in the gaseous mixture (*y* = 1 for a pure gas) and p is the total pressure.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] The value ${p^{\ominus }}$ is the standard pressure: it may be equal to 1 atm (101.325 kPa) or 1 bar (100 kPa) depending on the source of data, and should always be quoted.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] , the total number of moles of all the different components present in the mixture.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] The standard state of each component in the mixture is taken to be the pure substance, *i.e.* the pure substance has an activity of one.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] where fi is the Raoult's law activity coefficient: an activity coefficient of one indicates ideal behaviour according to Raoult's law.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] A solute in dilute solution usually follows Henry's law rather than Raoult's law, and it is more usual to express the composition of the solution in terms of the molar concentration c (in mol/L) or the molality b (in mol/kg) of the solute rather than in mole fractions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] The standard state of a dilute solution is a hypothetical solution of concentration *c*o = 1 mol/L (or molality *b*o = 1 mol/kg) which shows ideal behaviour (also referred to as "infinite-dilution" behaviour).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] The standard state, and hence the activity, depends on which measure of composition is used.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Molalities are often preferred as the volumes of non-ideal mixtures are not strictly additive and are also temperature-dependent: molalities do not depend on volume, whereas molar concentrations do.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] When the solute undergoes ionic dissociation in solution (for example a salt), the system becomes decidedly non-ideal and we need to take the dissociation process into consideration.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] One can define activities for the cations and anions separately (*a*+ and *a*–).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] In a liquid solution the activity coefficient of a given ion (e.g.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Ca2+) isn't measurable because it is experimentally impossible to independently measure the electrochemical potential of an ion in solution.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] (One cannot add cations without putting in anions at the same time).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Even though *γ*+ and *γ*– cannot be determined separately, *γ*± is a measurable quantity that can also be predicted for sufficiently dilute systems using Debye–Hückel theory.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] For electrolyte solutions at higher concentrations, Debye–Hückel theory needs to be extended and replaced, e.g., by a Pitzer electrolyte solution model (see external links below for examples).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] The most direct way of measuring the activity of a volatile species is to measure its equilibrium partial vapor pressure.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] For water as solvent, the water activity *aw* is the equilibrated relative humidity.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] For non-volatile components, such as sucrose or sodium chloride, this approach will not work since they do not have measurable vapor pressures at most temperatures.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] However, in such cases it is possible to measure the vapor pressure of the *solvent* instead.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Using the Gibbs–Duhem relation it is possible to translate the change in solvent vapor pressures with concentration into activities for the solute.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] The simplest way of determining how the activity of a component depends on pressure is by measurement of densities of solution, knowing that real solutions have deviations from the additivity of (molar) volumes of pure components compared to the (molar) volume of the solution.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] This involves the use of partial molar volumes, which measure the change in chemical potential with respect to pressure.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Another way to determine the activity of a species is through the manipulation of colligative properties, specifically freezing point depression.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] where b′ is the total equilibrium molality of solute determined by any colligative property measurement (in this case Δ*T*fus), b is the nominal molality obtained from titration and a is the activity of the species.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] There are also electrochemical methods that allow the determination of activity and its coefficient.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] The value of the mean ionic activity coefficient *γ*± of ions in solution can also be estimated with the Debye–Hückel equation, the Davies equation or the Pitzer equations.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] The prevailing view that single ion activities are unmeasurable, or perhaps even physically meaningless, has its roots in the work of Edward A.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] However, chemists have not given up the idea of single ion activities.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] For example, pH is defined as the negative logarithm of the hydrogen ion activity.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] By implication, if the prevailing view on the physical meaning and measurability of single ion activities is correct it relegates pH to the category of thermodynamically unmeasurable quantities.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Nevertheless, the concept of single ion activities continues to be discussed in the literature, and at least one author purports to define single ion activities in terms of purely thermodynamic quantities.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] The same author also proposes a method of measuring single ion activity coefficients based on purely thermodynamic processes.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] A different approach has a similar objective.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] where R is the gas constant and *μ*o *i* is the value of μi under standard conditions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Note that the choice of concentration scale affects both the activity and the standard state chemical potential, which is especially important when the reference state is the infinite dilution of a solute in a solvent.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Chemical potential has units of joules per mole (J/mol), or energy per amount of matter.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Chemical potential can be used to characterize the specific Gibbs free energy changes occurring in chemical reactions or other transformations.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Therefore, it is approximately equal to its concentration.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] The latter follows from any definition based on Raoult's law, because if we let the solute concentration *x*1 go to zero, the vapor pressure of the solvent p will go to p*.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Thus its activity *a* = ⁠*p*/*p**⁠ will go to unity.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] This means that if during a reaction in dilute solution more solvent is generated (the reaction produces water for example) we can typically set its activity to unity.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Solid and liquid activities do not depend very strongly on pressure because their molar volumes are typically small.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Graphite at 100 bars has an activity of only 1.01 if we choose *p*o = 1 bar as standard state.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Only at very high pressures do we need to worry about such changes.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Activity expressed in terms of pressure is called fugacity.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] Example values of activity coefficients of sodium chloride in aqueous solution are given in the table.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] In an ideal solution, these values would all be unity.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-chemistry] The deviations *tend* to become larger with increasing molality and temperature, but with some exceptions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] In thermodynamics, an **activity coefficient** is a factor used to account for deviation of a mixture of chemical substances from ideal behaviour.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Deviations from ideality are accommodated by modifying the concentration by an *activity coefficient*.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Analogously, expressions involving gases can be adjusted for non-ideality by scaling partial pressures by a fugacity coefficient.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] The concept of activity coefficient is closely linked to that of activity in chemistry.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] where *μ*o B is the chemical potential of a pure substance $\mathrm {B}$ , and $x_{\mathrm {B} }$ is the mole fraction of the substance in the mixture.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] where $\gamma _{\mathrm {B} }$ is the activity coefficient, which may itself depend on $x_{\mathrm {B} }$ .
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] As $\gamma _{\mathrm {B} }$ approaches 1, the substance behaves as if it were ideal.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] For instance, if $\gamma _{\mathrm {B} }$ ≈ 1, then Raoult's law is accurate.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] For $\gamma _{\mathrm {B} }$ > 1 and $\gamma _{\mathrm {B} }$ < 1, substance B shows positive and negative deviation from Raoult's law, respectively.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] A positive deviation implies that substance B is more volatile.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] In many cases, as $x_{\mathrm {B} }$ goes to zero, the activity coefficient of substance B approaches a constant; this relationship is Henry's law for the solvent.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] These relationships are related to each other through the Gibbs–Duhem equation.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Note that in general activity coefficients are dimensionless.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] with the convention $\lim _{x_{\mathrm {B} }\to 1}\gamma _{\mathrm {B} }=1\;.$ In other words: Pure liquids represent the ideal case.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] At infinite dilution, the activity coefficient approaches its limiting value, $\gamma _{\mathrm {B} }$ ∞.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] In other words: The compound shows nonideal behavior in the dilute case.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] The above definition of the activity coefficient is impractical if the compound does not exist as a pure liquid.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] This is often the case for electrolytes or biochemical compounds.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] The $^{\dagger }$ symbol has been used here to distinguish between the two kinds of activity coefficients.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Usually it is omitted, as it is clear from the context which kind is meant.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] But there are cases where both kinds of activity coefficients are needed and may even appear in the same equation, e.g., for solutions of salts in (water + alcohol) mixtures.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Modifying mole fractions or concentrations by activity coefficients gives the *effective activities* of the components, and hence allows expressions such as Raoult's law and equilibrium constants to be applied to both ideal and non-ideal mixtures.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Knowledge of activity coefficients is particularly important in the context of electrochemistry since the behaviour of electrolyte solutions is often far from ideal, even starting at low densities due to the effects of the ionic atmosphere.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Additionally, they are particularly important in the context of soil chemistry due to the low volumes of solvent and, consequently, the high concentration of electrolytes.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] For solution of substances which ionize in solution the activity coefficients of the cation and anion cannot be experimentally determined independently of each other because solution properties depend on both ions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Single ion activity coefficients must be linked to the activity coefficient of the dissolved electrolyte as if undissociated.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] In this case a mean stoichiometric activity coefficient of the dissolved electrolyte, *γ*±, is used.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] It is called stoichiometric because it expresses both the deviation from the ideality of the solution and the incomplete ionic dissociation of the ionic compound which occurs especially with the increase of its concentration.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] where $\gamma _{\mathrm {+} }$ and $\gamma _{\mathrm {-} }$ are the activity coefficients of the cation and anion respectively.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] The prevailing view that single ion activity coefficients are unmeasurable independently, or perhaps even physically meaningless, has its roots in the work of Guggenheim in the late 1920s.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] In this view, the partitioning of the physical electrochemical potentials into an activity contribution and a Galvani potential contribution is arbitrary, thus nonidealities in ion activities can be remapped to nonidealities in Galvani potential and vice versa.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Nevertheless, certain products of activities (such as $\gamma _{\pm }$ ) reflect a charge-neutral stoichiometry that is insensitive to this partitioning, so these products are physically meaningful even if the single-ion activities are not.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] However, chemists have never given up the idea of single ion activities, and by implication single ion activity coefficients.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] If the prevailing view on the physical meaning and measurability of single ion activities is correct then defining pH as the negative logarithm of the hydrogen ion activity places the quantity squarely in the unmeasurable category.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Recognizing this logical difficulty, International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) states that the activity-based definition of pH is a notional definition only.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Despite the prevailing negative view on the measurability of single ion coefficients, the concept of single ion activities continues to be discussed in the literature.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Activity coefficients may be determined experimentally by making measurements on non-ideal mixtures.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Use may be made of Raoult's law or Henry's law to provide a value for an ideal mixture against which the experimental value may be compared to obtain the activity coefficient.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Other colligative properties, such as osmotic pressure may also be used.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Activity coefficients can be determined by radiochemical methods.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Activity coefficients for binary mixtures are often reported at the infinite dilution of each component.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Because activity coefficient models simplify at infinite dilution, such empirical values can be used to estimate interaction energies.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Activity coefficients of electrolyte solutions may be calculated theoretically, using the Debye–Hückel equation or extensions such as the Davies equation, Pitzer equations or TCPC model.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Specific ion interaction theory (SIT) may also be used.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] For non-electrolyte solutions correlative methods such as UNIQUAC, NRTL, MOSCED or UNIFAC may be employed, provided fitted component-specific or model parameters are available.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] COSMO-RS is a theoretical method which is less dependent on model parameters as required information is obtained from quantum mechanics calculations specific to each molecule (sigma profiles) combined with a statistical thermodynamics treatment of surface segments.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] This simple model predicts activities of many species (dissolved undissociated gases such as CO2, H2S, NH3, undissociated acids and bases) to high ionic strengths (up to 5 mol/kg).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] The value of the constant *b* for CO2 is 0.11 at 10 °C and 0.20 at 330 °C.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] where *ν* is the number of ions produced from the dissociation of one molecule of the dissolved salt, *b* is the molality of the salt dissolved in water, *φ* is the osmotic coefficient of water, and the constant 55.51 represents the molality of water.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] In the above equation, the activity of a solvent (here water) is represented as inversely proportional to the number of particles of salt versus that of the solvent.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] where *A* and *B* are constants, *zi* is the valence number of the ion, and *I* is ionic strength.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Ionic activity coefficients can be calculated theoretically, for example by using the Debye–Hückel equation.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] The theoretical equation can be tested by combining the calculated single-ion activity coefficients to give mean values which can be compared to experimental values but only if the two ionic functions are strictly independent of one other (e.g. not determined by regression of experimental data).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] For concentrated ionic solutions the hydration of ions must be taken into consideration, as done by Stokes and Robinson in their hydration model from 1948.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] The activity coefficient of the electrolyte is split into electric and statistical components by E.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Glueckauf who modifies the Robinson–Stokes model.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] The statistical part includes hydration index number h, the number of ions from the dissociation and the ratio r between the apparent molar volume of the electrolyte and the molar volume of water and molality b.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] The Stokes–Robinson model has been analyzed and improved by other investigators.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] This means that the activity coefficients and the corresponding water activities are linked together fundamentally, regardless of molecular-level hypotheses.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Due to this high correlation, such hypotheses are not independent enough to be satisfactorily tested.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] The rise in activity coefficients found with most aqueous strong electrolyte systems can be explained by increasing electrostatic repulsions between ions of the same charge which are forced together as the available space between them decreases.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] In this way, the initial attractions between cations and anions at the low concentrations described by Debye and Hueckel are progressively overcome.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] It has been proposed that these electrostatic repulsions take place predominantly through the formation of so-called ion trios in which two ions of like charge interact, on average and at distance, with the same counterion as well as with each other.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] This model accurately reproduces the experimental patterns of activity and osmotic coefficients exhibited by numerous 3-ion aqueous electrolyte mixtures.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Similarly, the derivative of an activity coefficient with respect to pressure can be related to excess molar volume.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] At equilibrium, the sum of the chemical potentials of the reactants is equal to the sum of the chemical potentials of the products.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] The Gibbs free energy change for the reactions, Δr*G*, is equal to the difference between these sums and therefore, at equilibrium, is equal to zero.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] The sum *σμ*o S + *τμ*o T − *αμ*o A − *βμ*o B is the standard free energy change for the reaction, $\Delta _{\mathrm {r} }G^{\ominus }$ .
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] Note that activities and equilibrium constants are dimensionless numbers.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] It shows the relationship between standard free energy change and equilibrium constant.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] It also shows that an equilibrium constant is defined as a quotient of activities.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] In practical terms this is inconvenient.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] where [S] denotes the concentration of S, etc.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/activity-coefficient] which applies under the conditions that the activity quotient has a particular (constant) value.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] The **Bromley equation** was developed in 1973 by Leroy A.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] Bromley with the objective of calculating activity coefficients for aqueous electrolyte solutions whose concentrations are above the range of validity of the Debye–Hückel equation.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] This equation, together with Specific ion interaction theory (SIT) and Pitzer equations is important for the understanding of the behaviour of ions dissolved in natural waters such as rivers, lakes and sea-water.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] Guggenheim had proposed an extension of the Debye-Hückel equation which is the basis of SIT theory.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] $\gamma _{\pm }$ is the mean molal activity coefficient.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] The first term on the right-hand side is the Debye–Hückel term, with a constant, *A*, and the ionic strength *I*. β is an interaction coefficient and *b* the molality of the electrolyte.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] As the concentration decreases so the second term becomes less important until, at very low concentrations, the Debye-Hückel equation gives a satisfactory account of the activity coefficient.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] Bromley observed that experimental values of ${\frac {1}{z_{+}z_{-}}}\log \gamma _{\pm }$ were often approximately proportional to ionic strength.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] At 25 °C *Aγ* is equal to 0.511 and ρ is equal to one.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] Bromley tabulated values of the interaction coefficient *B*.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] He noted that the equation gave satisfactory agreement with experimental data up to ionic strength of 6 molal, though with decreasing precision when extrapolating to very high ionic strength.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] As with other equations, it is not satisfactory when there is ion association as, for example, with divalent metal sulfates.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] where the + subscript refers to a cation and the minus subscript refers to an anion.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] Bromley's equation can easily be transformed for the calculation of osmotic coefficients, and Bromley also proposed extensions to multicomponent solutions and for the effect of temperature change.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] A modified version of the Bromley equation has been used extensively by Madariaga and co-workers.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] In a comparison of Bromley, SIT and Pitzer models, little difference was found in the quality of fit.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] The Bromley equation is essentially an empirical equation.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] The *B* parameters are relatively easy to determine.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] However, SIT theory, as extended by Scatchard. and Ciavatta is much more widely used.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] By contrast the Pitzer equation is based on rigorous thermodynamics.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] The determination Pitzer parameters is more laborious.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] Whilst the Bromley and SIT approaches are based on pair-wise interactions between oppositely charged ions, the Pitzer approach also allows for interactions between three ions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] These equations are important for the understanding of the behaviour of ions in natural waters such as rivers, lakes and sea-water.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/bromley-equation] For some complex electrolytes, Ge et al. obtained the new set of Bromley parameters using up-to-date measured or critically reviewed osmotic coefficient or activity coefficient data.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] Brønsted was born in Varde, Denmark on 22 February 1879.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] His mother died shortly after his birth, and his father died when Brønsted was 14 years old; he then moved to Copenhagen with his older sister and his stepmother.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] In 1897, Brønsted began his studies as a chemical engineer at the Polytechnic Institute in Copenhagen.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] After his first degree, Brønsted changed fields and received his magister degree in chemistry in 1902 from the University of Copenhagen.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] In 1905, he became an assistant at the Chemical Institute and obtained his doctoral degree in 1908.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] In the same year, Brønsted became a professor of physical and inorganic chemistry at the University of Copenhagen.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] In 1929, Brønsted was a visiting professor at Yale University.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] His research gained worldwide recognition, resulting in four Nobel Prize nominations, a gold H.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] C. Ørsted Medal and being appointed as a fellow of the Royal Society and a member of the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] Brønsted married Charlotte Warberg, whom he met during his first degree.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] In World War II, Brønsted's opposition to the Nazis led to his election to the Danish parliament in 1947, but he was too ill to take his seat and died shortly after the election.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] Early in his career, Brønsted studied chemical thermodynamics and later studied electrolyte solutions and carried out an extensive series of solubility measurements.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] These measurements led him to establish general laws which were later confirmed when the Debye–Hückel theory was proposed.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] Brønsted is best known for his work on reaction kinetics, in particular acid–base reactions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] In 1923, he recognized that acid–base reactions involved the transfer of a proton, from the acid (proton donor) to the base (proton acceptor).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] Almost simultaneously and independently, the British chemist Martin Lowry arrived at the same conclusion, thus the name Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] Lewis proposed an electronic theory of acid–base reactions, but both theories remain commonly used.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] Later in his career, Brønsted kept studying reaction kinetics, with a special focus on reactions taking place in non-aqueous solutions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] He also developed some work about the effect of molecular size on the thermodynamical properties of hydrocarbons, polymers and colloids.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/brønsted] He also worked with the Nobel prize winner George de Hevesy on isotope separation by fractional distillation.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] In chemistry, **concentration** is the abundance of a constituent divided by the total volume of a mixture.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] Several types of mathematical description can be distinguished: *mass concentration*, *molar concentration*, *number concentration*, and *volume concentration*.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] The concentration can refer to any kind of chemical mixture, but most frequently refers to solutes and solvents in solutions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] The molar (amount) concentration has variants, such as normal concentration and osmotic concentration.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] **Dilution** is reduction of concentration, e.g., by adding solvent to a solution.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] The verb "to concentrate" means to increase concentration, the opposite of dilute.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] Often in informal, non-technical language, concentration is described in a qualitative way, through the use of adjectives such as "dilute" for solutions of relatively low concentration and "concentrated" for solutions of relatively high concentration.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] To **concentrate** a solution, one must add more solute (for example, alcohol), or reduce the amount of solvent (for example, water).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] By contrast, to **dilute** a solution, one must add more solvent, or reduce the amount of solute.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] Unless two substances are miscible, there exists a concentration at which no further solute will dissolve in a solution.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] At this point, the solution is said to be saturated.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] If additional solute is added to a saturated solution, it will not dissolve, except in certain circumstances, when supersaturation may occur.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] Instead, phase separation will occur, leading to coexisting phases, either completely separated or mixed as a suspension.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] The point of saturation depends on many variables, such as ambient temperature and the precise chemical nature of the solvent and solute.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] Concentrations are often called **levels**, reflecting the mental schema of levels on the vertical axis of a graph, which can be high or low (for example, "high serum levels of bilirubin" are concentrations of bilirubin in the blood serum that are greater than normal).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] However, more commonly the unit mol/L (= mol/dm3) is used.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] Being dimensionless, it is expressed as a number, e.g., 0.18 or 18%.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] There seems to be no standard notation in the English literature.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] The letter $\sigma _{i}$ used here is normative in German literature ().
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] Several other quantities can be used to describe the composition of a mixture.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] These should **not** be called concentrations.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] Normality is defined as the molar concentration $c_{i}$ divided by an equivalence factor $f_{\mathrm {eq} }$ .
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] Since the definition of the equivalence factor depends on context (which reaction is being studied), the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry and National Institute of Standards and Technology discourage the use of normality.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] However, the deprecated parts-per notation is often used to describe small mole fractions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] If $n_{i}$ is much smaller than $n_{\mathrm {tot} }$ , the mole ratio is almost identical to the mole fraction.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] However, the deprecated parts-per notation is often used to describe small mole ratios.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] However, the deprecated parts-per notation is often used to describe small mass fractions.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] If $m_{i}$ is much smaller than $m_{\mathrm {tot} }$ , the mass ratio is almost identical to the mass fraction.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] However, the deprecated parts-per notation is often used to describe small mass ratios.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/concentration] Concentration depends on the variation of the volume of the solution with temperature, due mainly to thermal expansion.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] In theoretical chemistry, **Specific ion Interaction Theory** (**SIT theory)** is a theory used to estimate single-ion activity coefficients in electrolyte solutions at relatively high concentrations.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] It does so by taking into consideration *interaction coefficients* between the various ions present in solution.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] Interaction coefficients are determined from equilibrium constant values obtained with solutions at various ionic strengths.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] The determination of SIT interaction coefficients also yields the value of the equilibrium constant at infinite dilution.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] This theory arises from the need to derive activity coefficients of solutes when their concentrations are too high to be predicted accurately by the Debye–Hückel theory.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] Activity coefficients are needed because an equilibrium constant is defined in chemical thermodynamics as the ratio of activities but is usually measured using concentrations.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] The protonation of a monobasic acid will be used to simplify the presentation.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] where {HA}, {H+}, and {A–} represent the activity of the corresponding chemical species.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] The role of water in the association equilibrium is ignored as in all but the most concentrated solutions the activity of water is constant.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] *K* is defined here as an *association* constant, the reciprocal of an acid dissociation constant.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] Each activity term { } can be expressed as the product of a concentration [ ] and an activity coefficient γ.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] where the square brackets represent a concentration and γ is an activity coefficient.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] Thus the equilibrium constant can be expressed as a product of a concentration ratio and an activity coefficient ratio.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] It is a common practice to determine equilibrium constants in solutions containing an electrolyte at high ionic strength such that the activity coefficients are effectively constant.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] However, when the ionic strength is changed the measured equilibrium constant will also change, so there is a need to estimate individual (single ion) activity coefficients.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] Debye–Hückel theory provides a means to do this, but it is accurate only at very low concentrations.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] Hence the need for an extension to Debye–Hückel theory.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] SIT theory, discussed here and Pitzer equations.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] SIT theory was first proposed by Brønsted in 1922 and was further developed by Guggenheim in 1955.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] Scatchard extended the theory in 1936 to allow the interaction coefficients to vary with ionic strength.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] The theory was mainly of theoretical interest until 1945 because of the difficulty of determining equilibrium constants before the glass electrode was invented.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] Subsequently, Ciavatta developed the theory further in 1980.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] The activity coefficient of the *j*th ion in solution is written as γj when concentrations are on the molal concentration scale and as *y*j when concentrations are on the molar concentration scale.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] (The molality scale is preferred in thermodynamics because molal concentrations are independent of temperature).
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] where *z* is the electrical charge on the ion, *I* is the ionic strength, ε and *b* are interaction coefficients and *m* and *c* are concentrations.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] The summation extends over the other ions present in solution, which includes the ions produced by the background electrolyte.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] The first term in these expressions comes from Debye–Hückel theory.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] The second term shows how the contributions from "interaction" are dependent on concentration.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] Thus, the interaction coefficients are used as corrections to Debye–Hückel theory when concentrations are higher than the region of validity of that theory.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] In the example of a monobasic acid HA, assuming that the background electrolyte is the salt NaNO3, the interaction coefficients will be for interaction between H+ and NO3−, and between A− and Na+.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] Firstly, equilibrium constants are determined at a number of different ionic strengths, at a chosen temperature and particular background electrolyte.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] The interaction coefficients are then determined by fitting to the observed equilibrium constant values.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] The procedure also provides the value of *K* at infinite dilution.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] It is not limited to monobasic acids. and can also be applied to metal complexes.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] The SIT and Pitzer approaches have been compared recently.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] The Bromley equation has also been compared to both SIT and Pitzer equations.
[src:specific-ion-interaction-theory/specific-ion-interaction-theory] It has been shown that the SIT equation is a practical simplification of a more complicated hypothesis, that is rigorously applicable only at trace concentrations of reactant and product species immersed in a surrounding electrolyte medium.
